\b \cf0 Heading: 
\b0 Referencing systems\
\

\b Description: 
\b0 A two-column table containing information about (1) author date referencing systems, and (2) footnote/endnote referencing systems.\cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sl340\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Narration: 
\b0 There are two broad categories of referencing styles. One group are know as author-date styles, and you can spot these because in the essay text, every citation consists of an author\'92s surname and a date of publication. Also, the reference list at the end will be in alphabetical order. \
\
One of the styles that belongs to this group is \'96 among others \'96 APA, which stands for the American Psychological Association. This is the style that is commonly used in the School of Nursing at RMIT.\
\
The other group of styles is the footnote or endnote group. These use just a number in the text to signify that a certain piece of information has come from another source. Footnote and endnote styles are commonly used in medical sciences, and some of the journals you will read may use the style from this referencing system. When comparing footnoting with author-date systems, one group\'92s style is no better than the other. \
\
There is a general tendency for the scientific and medical field to use footnote styles, because researchers are focused on the data and it is less important to know who particularly found or said something. The humanities tend to favour author-date systems because these fields are mainly constructed by theories, so it is very necessary to know which writer or expert has put forward a certain theory or idea.\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \cell \row

