\b \cf0 Heading:
\b0  APA style: in-text referencing\
\

\b Description:
\b0  Examples of in-text referencing with a focus on two different types: subject prominent referencing and author prominent referencing.\
\
The subject prominent first example reads \'93In order to manage well, it is helpful to have the support and guidance of the wider nurse management community (Harper & Miller, 2009)\'94.\
\
The author prominent example reads \'93Harper and Miller (2009) emphasise that establishing mentorships with other nurse managers is important for effective leadership\'94.\cell 
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sl340\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Narration: 
\b0 This is what APA looks like in text. You can make your reference subject prominent. That means that the information comes first, and the author and date are mentioned in a bracket at the end of the borrowed information. \
\
The next sentence is similar, but this time we have not just used Harper and Miller\'92s idea, we have used their exact words. It\'92s permissible to do so, but only if their sentence emphasises the point that you want to emphasise, and you can\'92t put it better yourself. When using a direct quote, as this is, you do have to enclose the words in quotation marks, and also include the page number in the citation. For a website, you should to include the paragraph number instead.\
\
In this case, we directly quoted a whole sentence, it would be possible to quote half a sentence and finish the rest of the sentence in your own words if that suited your purpose. The other way to do an in-text citation is to make it author prominent; in this structure the author\'92s name becomes part the sentence itself. With this structure we say that Harper and Miller argue or advise or comment or state. It\'92s a good idea to have a collection of these words to pick from, because \'91state\'92 tends to get overused.\
\
This first sentence is a paraphrase, so you only need the year of publication, and that is still in brackets. The second sentence here is another direct quote, and once again, we need the page number. Note that when you use a direct quote, you have to write it exactly as you found it. However, it is permissible to change a capital letter to a lowercase letter if it suits the structure of your sentence. The capital N for \'91Networking\'92 was changed to lowercase here because the original capital N would look strange in the middle of a sentence.\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \cell \row

